{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17631882","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17631882"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:34:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:34:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17408"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17408","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17408"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10098"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70497"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10098","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10098"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17408"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55961"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"7796"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23657"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23660"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70497","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70497"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA research team is designing a clinical trial to test the effectiveness of a new medication for hypertension.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the key characteristic of a randomised controlled trial?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Participant selection based on specific risk factors","Sequential allocation of participants to study groups","Random allocation of participants to study groups","Participant choice of group allocation","Researcher choice of group allocation"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe defining feature of a randomised controlled trial is \u003Cstrong\u003Erandom allocation of participants to study groups\u003C/strong\u003E. This process ensures that any potential confounding factors are distributed equally between groups, minimising selection bias and allowing for valid comparison between intervention and control groups.\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cul\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESequential allocation of participants to study groups\u003C/strong\u003E introduces potential selection bias as allocation could be predicted and manipulated.\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParticipant selection based on specific risk factors\u003C/strong\u003E relates to initial eligibility criteria rather than the method of allocating participants to groups.\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EResearcher choice of group allocation\u003C/strong\u003E would introduce significant selection bias as researchers may consciously or unconsciously allocate participants based on their characteristics.\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParticipant choice of group allocation\u003C/strong\u003E would introduce self-selection bias as participants may choose groups based on their preferences or perceived benefits.\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E    \u003Cp\u003ERandom allocation is typically achieved using computer-generated sequences or random number tables. This methodology, combined with appropriate blinding and control groups, makes randomised controlled trials the gold standard for evaluating healthcare interventions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A randomised controlled trial randomly allocates participants to intervention and control groups to minimise selection bias.","Double-blinding in clinical trials means neither participants nor researchers know group allocation during the study.","The control group in a randomised controlled trial provides a comparison to determine the true effect of the intervention."],"references":["Shultz JM, Sullivan LM, Galea S. Public Health: An Introduction to the Science and Practice of Population Health. Springer Publishing Company; 2021.","Ray, Sumantra, and others (eds), Oxford Handbook of Clinical and Healthcare Research, 1, Oxford Medical Handbooks (Oxford, 2016; online edn, Oxford Academic, 1 Mar. 2016), https://doi.org/10.1093/med/9780199608478.001.0001, accessed 12 Dec. 2024."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55961"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17408"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55961","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55961"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-15T18:50:55+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-15T18:51:36+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10098"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70497"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identi